  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Connecticut received $14.5B in federal contract obligations in FY2026 to date. Obligations come from 19,278 awards with an average award size of $751K, and obligations were down 58.8% year over year; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). The Department of Defense accounted for $14.2B of obligations, and the remaining top buying agencies each contributed amounts in the millions, led by the Department of Veterans Affairs at $105M and the Department of Homeland Security at $102M. Major vendors include ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B, RTX CORPORATION at $3B, and SIKORSKY AIRCRAFT CORPORATION at $2.3B. Top industries by obligations include Engineering Services at $6.8B, Aircraft Manufacturing at $2.6B, and Ship Building and Repairing at $1.6B. Historical annual obligations show variability, with FY21 at $18.4B, FY22 at $22.3B, FY23 at $26B, FY24 at $20B, FY25 at $35.1B, and FY26 at $14.5B.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What explains the FY2026 to date total?",
        "body": "The FY2026 to date total of $14.5B is dominated by the Department of Defense, which accounted for $14.2B. Large vendor awards to ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION ($8.3B), RTX CORPORATION ($3B), and SIKORSKY AIRCRAFT CORPORATION ($2.3B) concentrated a sizable share of obligations. The state’s industry mix—led by Engineering Services ($6.8B) and Aircraft Manufacturing ($2.6B)—also aligns with the top vendors and the DoD-driven spending profile."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How is spending concentrated across agencies, vendors, and industries?",
        "body": "Spending is highly concentrated: one agency, the Department of Defense, contributed $14.2B of the $14.5B total, while the next nine agencies range from $105M to $5M. The top three vendors—ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION ($8.3B), RTX CORPORATION ($3B), and SIKORSKY AIRCRAFT CORPORATION ($2.3B)—account for the largest vendor shares. Engineering Services ($6.8B) and Aircraft Manufacturing ($2.6B) are the leading industries by obligations, followed by Ship Building and Repairing ($1.6B)."
      }
    ]
  },
